nd activities in which Canadians have found something transcendant or revelatory. Each of the chapters in Locations of the Sacred can be read independently as a discrete analysis of its subject. Taken as a whole, the essays make up a powerful argument for a new way of looking at the religious in contemporary Canada — not in the traditional ways of being religious, but in activities and locations previously thought to be “secular.” Thus, the domains and modes of the religious are expanded, not restricted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literature (English)xHistory and criticismx20th centuryxCanada. 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity in literature. 0aReligion and culturexCanada. 0aReligion and culturezCanada. 0aReligion and culture. 0aReligion dans la littérature. 0aReligion et culturexCanada. 0aReligion in literature. 0aSpirituality in literature. 0aSpiritualité dans la littérature. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aReligion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920757840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207578423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207578/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles